    <section anchor="segmented-numbers">
      <name>Segmented Numbers and Use Cases</name>
      <t>A core feature of Ten64 is the "Segmented Number" representing a list 
      of integers delimited by periods. E.g., "#0.1.2;" expands to integers 0, 
      1, and 2.</t>
      
      <section anchor="big-decimals">
        <name>BigDecimals</name>
        <t>Ten64 easily represents arbitrarily precise BigDecimals by encoding 
        the EXACT number of decimal places. E.g., "#-1.8;" expands to -1 and 8 
        (which contextually translates to the decimal -1.8). This mitigates 
        the floating-point truncation issues observed in JSON.</t>
      </section>

      <section anchor="temporal-types">
        <name>Dates, Datetimes, and Timestamps</name>
        <t>Ten64 uses Segmented Numbers to heavily condense date formats. While 
        <xref target="ISO8601"/> provides standard string representations, 
        Ten64 condenses these logically:</t>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Dates:</strong> Encoded as the year followed by a dot, 
          one char for the month, and one for the day (e.g., "#Vv.21;" 
          expands to 2023-02-01).</li>
          <li><strong>Datetimes:</strong> Timezone, hour, and minute each 
          require one char appended to the date (e.g., "#Vv.216jR;" expands 
          to 2023-02-01 CST 7:53 PM).</li>
          <li><strong>MiliTimestamps:</strong> Appends a char for seconds and 
          uses a dot for milliseconds (e.g.,#Vv.216jR1.2;  expands to
          2023-02-01 CST 7:53:01.2 PM or with miliseconds expanded 2023-02-01
          CST 7:53:01.002 PM).</li>
          <li><strong>NanoTimestamps:</strong> Appends additional characters 
          representing nanoseconds not tracked as milliseconds. (e.g., 
          #Vv.216jR1.2.7; expands to 2023-02-01 CST 7:53:01.2.7 PM or with
          nanoseconds expanded 2023-02-01 CST 7:53:01.002000007 PM)</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section anchor="lists-and-points">
        <name>Lists and Geometric Points</name>
        <t>Ten64 supports 1D lists separated by commas (e.g., "#1,2,3,4;") 
        and N-dimensional points combined with decimal segmentation 
        (e.g., "#1.2.3,4.5.6;" expands to a list of 3D points).</t>
      </section>
    </section>

